{"parse":{"title":"Immigration sign","pageid":18305118,"revid":846167288,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:W54_Special_(CA-San_Ysidro)_-vector.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/W54_Special_%28CA-San_Ysidro%29_-vector.svg/220px-W54_Special_%28CA-San_Ysidro%29_-vector.svg.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"157\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/W54_Special_%28CA-San_Ysidro%29_-vector.svg/330px-W54_Special_%28CA-San_Ysidro%29_-vector.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bb/W54_Special_%28CA-San_Ysidro%29_-vector.svg/440px-W54_Special_%28CA-San_Ysidro%29_-vector.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"700\" data-file-height=\"500\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:W54_Special_(CA-San_Ysidro)_-vector.svg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>The sign</div></div></div>\n<p>The <b>immigration sign</b> was a <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Numbered_Highways\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"United States Numbered Highways\">U.S. highway</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Road_traffic_safety\" title=\"Road traffic safety\">safety sign</a> warning motorists to avoid <a href=\"/wiki/Immigration_to_the_United_States\" title=\"Immigration to the United States\">immigrants</a> darting across the road. It depicted a man, woman, and child with pigtails running. The signs were erected in response to over one hundred immigrant pedestrian deaths due to traffic collisions from 1987 to 1990 in two corridors along <a href=\"/wiki/Interstate_5_in_California\" title=\"Interstate 5 in California\">Interstate 5</a> along the <a href=\"/wiki/San_Ysidro_Port_of_Entry\" title=\"San Ysidro Port of Entry\">San Ysidro Port of Entry</a> at the <a href=\"/wiki/Mexico%E2%80%93United_States_border\" title=\"Mexico\u2013United States border\">Mexico\u2013United States border</a> and approximately 50 miles (80&#160;km) north at the <a href=\"/wiki/San_Clemente,_California\" title=\"San Clemente, California\">San Clemente</a> <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Border_Patrol\" title=\"United States Border Patrol\">United States Border Patrol</a> <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Border_Patrol_interior_checkpoints\" title=\"United States Border Patrol interior checkpoints\">checkpoint</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Marine_Corps_Base_Camp_Pendleton\" title=\"Marine Corps Base Camp Pendleton\">Camp Pendleton</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Design_and_reuse\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Design and reuse</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Immigration_sign&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Immigrant smugglers adopted the tactic of dropping off their human cargo on the shoulder or median of the freeway prior to passing through the checkpoint. Once past the checkpoint, the smugglers would wait for the immigrants to rejoin before proceeding to the final destination. However, in order to avoid the checkpoint (straddling the northbound lanes of the freeway), the immigrants would have to cross the freeway to the southbound shoulder. At the Camp Pendleton checkpoint, immigrants were precluded from passing the checkpoint on the northbound shoulder by rugged terrain and random Marine patrols.<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The running family silhouette supplemented all-text signs advising drivers \"CAUTION WATCH FOR PEOPLE CROSSING ROAD\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-NYT_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-NYT-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Caltrans_CAUTION_PEOPLE_CROSSING.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Caltrans_CAUTION_PEOPLE_CROSSING.svg/220px-Caltrans_CAUTION_PEOPLE_CROSSING.svg.png\" width=\"220\" height=\"220\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Caltrans_CAUTION_PEOPLE_CROSSING.svg/330px-Caltrans_CAUTION_PEOPLE_CROSSING.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Caltrans_CAUTION_PEOPLE_CROSSING.svg/440px-Caltrans_CAUTION_PEOPLE_CROSSING.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"500\" data-file-height=\"500\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Caltrans_CAUTION_PEOPLE_CROSSING.svg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>All-text sign.</div></div></div>\n<p>The running family silhouette signs were erected starting in September 1990,<sup id=\"cite_ref-SDUT_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SDUT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> and it is not known how effective they were in reducing traffic strike fatalities before the implementation of other physical measures. Eventually, Caltrans built a tall fence in the I-5 median south of the San Clemente checkpoint, which effectively precluded the checkpoint-avoidance traffic-crossing tactic at Camp Pendleton,<sup id=\"cite_ref-SDUT_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SDUT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> and the Border Patrol implemented <a href=\"/wiki/Operation_Gatekeeper\" title=\"Operation Gatekeeper\">Operation Gatekeeper</a> in 1995, which erected a tall fence along the San Diego\u2013Tijuana border, moving illegal immigration attempts further east into the desert.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SDUT_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SDUT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>As of 2008 and later confirmed in July 2017, one sign remains in California,<sup id=\"cite_ref-ICT-081012_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ICT-081012-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and there are no plans to replace it as it is largely obsolete. The number of people apprehended while illegally crossing the border in the region has seen a 95% decline over thirty years, going from 628,000 arrested in 1986 to 31,891 in 2016.<sup id=\"cite_ref-LATimes_20170707_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LATimes_20170707-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Design_and_reuse\">Design and reuse</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Immigration_sign&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Design and reuse\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/California_Department_of_Transportation\" title=\"California Department of Transportation\">Caltrans</a> graphic artist John Hood, a <a href=\"/wiki/Navajo_people\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Navajo people\">Navajo</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Vietnam_veteran\" title=\"Vietnam veteran\">Vietnam War veteran</a>, created the image as an assignment in response to the sharp rise in immigrant traffic deaths.<sup id=\"cite_ref-LAT_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LAT-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The image was developed to elicit immediate recognition of the potential traffic hazard and to illustrate the potential running motion with the little girl's flowing pigtails.<sup id=\"cite_ref-LAT_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-LAT-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> The final design process took approximately a week, and Hood drew inspiration from both his experiences in Vietnam as well as stories from his Navajo parents.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SDUT_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SDUT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Hood has stated the man's profile is similar to <a href=\"/wiki/Cesar_Chavez\" title=\"Cesar Chavez\">Cesar Chavez</a>, and the child was depicted as a little girl being dragged along because \"little girls are dear to the heart, especially for fathers.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-ICT-081012_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ICT-081012-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> Hood likened the immigrants' plight to the <a href=\"/wiki/Long_Walk_of_the_Navajo\" title=\"Long Walk of the Navajo\">Long Walk of the Navajo</a> to their present-day reservation in northeastern New Mexico in 1864.<sup id=\"cite_ref-ICT-081012_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ICT-081012-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303468\">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class=\"templatequote\"><p>It was troublesome that there was a mass exodus, especially families. And when you talk about families, you talk about children. They were getting slaughtered in the freeways. The children don\u2019t know what\u2019s happening and why they are there. [And] why their parents are doing it. They just know this is not their home. The sign conveys that they are away from home. And the children are asking, \u2018What are we running for?\u2019 Today, even when I watch parents walking in malls with their kids, it\u2019s like they are dragging them. That was the idea: clutching something that is dear to our heart.</p><div class=\"templatequotecite\">\u2014&#8201;<cite>John Hood, Caltrans graphic artist, Interview with Victor Morales<sup id=\"cite_ref-ICT-081012_3-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-ICT-081012-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup></cite></div>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Since its deployment it has become a <a href=\"/wiki/Popular_culture\" title=\"Popular culture\">pop culture</a> icon as it appeared on T-shirts and <a href=\"/wiki/Anti-immigration\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Anti-immigration\">anti-immigration</a> advertisements in various incarnations.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SDUT_2-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SDUT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> It was exhibited in the <a href=\"/wiki/Smithsonian_Institution\" title=\"Smithsonian Institution\">Smithsonian Institution</a>'s permanent exhibition on transportation,<sup id=\"cite_ref-SDUT_2-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SDUT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> and British street artist <a href=\"/wiki/Banksy\" title=\"Banksy\">Banksy</a> used a modified version of the silhouette family in his <i>Kite-2</i> artwork exhibited on Los Angeles-area streets in early 2011.<sup id=\"cite_ref-COLOR_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-COLOR-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> The silhouette family is also a popular target of parody, spawning variants including ones where the family is depicted wearing caps and gowns (referencing the <a href=\"/wiki/DREAM_Act\" title=\"DREAM Act\">DREAM Act</a>); as Joseph, Mary and Jesus;<sup id=\"cite_ref-SCPR_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SCPR-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> as a beer label;<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> and one where they are wearing Pilgrim gear.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SDUT_2-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SDUT-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In June 2018, political cartoonist <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Rob_Rogers_(Cartoonist)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Rob Rogers (Cartoonist) (page does not exist)\">Rob Rogers</a> was fired from the <a href=\"/wiki/Pittsburgh_Post-Gazette\" title=\"Pittsburgh Post-Gazette\">Pittsburgh Post-Gazette</a> after submitting a series of cartoons critical of President Donald Trump, one of which depicted a version of the caution sign with the trailing child being torn away by a silhouetted Trump.<sup id=\"cite_ref-WAPO_9-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-WAPO-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Immigration_sign&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-NYT-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-NYT_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-NYT_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-NYT_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Mydans, Seth (7 January 1991). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1991/01/07/us/one-last-deadly-crossing-for-illegal-aliens.html\">\"One Last Deadly Crossing for Illegal Aliens\"</a>. <i>The New York Times</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">15 June</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+New+York+Times&amp;rft.atitle=One+Last+Deadly+Crossing+for+Illegal+Aliens&amp;rft.date=1991-01-07&amp;rft.au=Mydans%2C+Seth&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F1991%2F01%2F07%2Fus%2Fone-last-deadly-crossing-for-illegal-aliens.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AImmigration+sign\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-SDUT-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-SDUT_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SDUT_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SDUT_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SDUT_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SDUT_2-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SDUT_2-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-SDUT_2-6\"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Berestein, Leslie (10 April 2005). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.signonsandiego.com/uniontrib/20050410/news_1n10signs.html\">\"Highway safety sign becomes running story on immigration\"</a>. <i>San Diego Union-Tribune</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">15 June</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=San+Diego+Union-Tribune&amp;rft.atitle=Highway+safety+sign+becomes+running+story+on+immigration&amp;rft.date=2005-04-10&amp;rft.au=Berestein%2C+Leslie&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.signonsandiego.com%2Funiontrib%2F20050410%2Fnews_1n10signs.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AImmigration+sign\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-ICT-081012-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-ICT-081012_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-ICT-081012_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-ICT-081012_3-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-ICT-081012_3-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Morales, Victor (12 October 2008). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/news/iconic-sign-evokes-connection-to-long-walk/\">\"Iconic sign evokes connection to Long Walk\"</a>. Indian Country Today<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">10 July</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Iconic+sign+evokes+connection+to+Long+Walk&amp;rft.pub=Indian+Country+Today&amp;rft.date=2008-10-12&amp;rft.au=Morales%2C+Victor&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Findiancountrymedianetwork.com%2Fnews%2Ficonic-sign-evokes-connection-to-long-walk%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AImmigration+sign\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-LATimes_20170707-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-LATimes_20170707_4-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Carcamo, Cindy (7 July 2017). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-immigrants-running-road-sign-20170614-htmlstory.html\">\"With only one left, iconic yellow road sign showing running immigrants now borders on the extinct\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Los_Angeles_Times\" title=\"Los Angeles Times\">Los Angeles Times</a></i>. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20170708231207/http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-immigrants-running-road-sign-20170614-htmlstory.